segments.text: Testing, one, two, three.
Testing, yes.
It's working.
No problem.
Just say that I think you were closing by saying that I don't see any reference to the Louisiana-Missouri plant in current gasification papers.
And I don't think that the present investigators are not aware of the Louisiana plant.
But it may be that there's just been nothing published on it that I know.
I don't know.
As far as I know, there's been no
I haven't seen any data from the Louisiana plant.
And what McGee and Cattell would know this better than I, I don't think there's been a paper on the gasification part of the plant.
I know there's only one on that purification.
I don't know whether anything has been published on the Burgess.
I mean, in the public literature, not government interim reports or that sort of thing.
I don't know.
Do you think they were on the right track?
Oh, I do.
I do.
There's renewed interest now in Fisher Tropes.
ERDA has several contracts out, looking at Fisher Tropes, and one is with Exxon.
I think that
But it was a rough approach.
Let me just step back one step.
Did you have any dealing with the German scientists who were brought to Louisiana, Missouri?
The only thing I can recall, really, is having met them when they were here in Morgantown, and having our pictures taken.
I don't know whether they'd be around for a while.
And I can only recall three of them.
I don't know how many there were.
We got five or six, I would imagine.
You mentioned a Dr. Opelt.
Hoobman.
And Hoobman.
And Donoff.
And Donoff.
Did you get any other names?
Let's see.
We have... Oh, I haven't got them here.
We have a list of the seven signs.
Oh, but there's seven?
Yes.
Because we have a list of the Bureau of Managed Reports for the seven signs.
Yes.
O-P-B-E-L-T-H-U-B-M-A-N-N-D-O-N-A-T-H.
But of course, if the purification wasn't based upon the German process, you wouldn't have had too much interaction with the Germans.
No.
But I think that those men probably were more of gasification and hydrogenation and not as much involved in purification.
I don't know whether Dr. Ruppelt's around now, but I think he'd have been with Babcock and Wilcox at one time.
And you developed a process that would purify 5,000 cubic feet?
Yeah, a small pilot plant.
That was before we had the station out here in Coventry River.
It was really a Gerger purification design.
In fact, Gerger constructed it for us.
Did you use any German vessels or pumps or anything like that?
No, it was all manufactured here.
In fact, at that time, you had to have a very good justification if you purchased any foreign equipment for use in government work.

Even as far as the instrumentation like the analytical instrumentation such as x-ray diffraction or infrared or ultraviolet, you had to have a very strong justification if you wanted to buy it from overseas.
I think that's used at some point now.
So in your opinion, it really wouldn't stand to reason for someone to undertake these same efforts again to

experiments to start experimenting with gas purification when in fact it has been successfully accomplished the only area that i think there can be improvement would be in the liquid absorbent for removing hydrogen sulfide if you can get a greater sort of that has a greater capacity

Although I think the bent-fill process is probably going to be very hard to beat since its absorption and regeneration take place at pretty much the same temperature, so you don't have much cooling of the liquid when you regenerate it.
You don't use as much steam to regenerate it.
Well, I'm not too familiar with the Stretford process.
McGee would be on that.
That would be an improvement, I'm sure, over the old cost process for producing sulfur from hydrogen sulfide.
That would be an operation at the StenPay plant in Brewston, so we can actually get data from that.
